To rationalize the denominator, we multiply both the numerator and denominator by $\sqrt{7}$. This is done because $\sqrt{7} \cdot \sqrt{7} = 7$, which eliminates the square root in the denominator, resulting in a rational expression.
Step 1: Multiply both the numerator and denominator by $\sqrt{7}$.

$$\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2\sqrt{7}} &= \frac{1}{2\sqrt{7}} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{7}}{\sqrt{7}}
\end{align*}$$

Step 2: Simplify the numerator and denominator.

$$\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2\sqrt{7}} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{7}}{\sqrt{7}} &= \frac{1 \cdot \sqrt{7}}{2\sqrt{7} \cdot \sqrt{7}}\\
&= \frac{\sqrt{7}}{2 \cdot 7}
\end{align*}$$

Step 3: Simplify the denominator.

$$\begin{align*}
\frac{\sqrt{7}}{2 \cdot 7} &= \frac{\sqrt{7}}{14}
\end{align*}$$
The rationalized form of $\frac{1}{2\sqrt{7}}$ is $\boxed{\frac{\sqrt{7}}{14}}$.

The key insight in this problem is to recognize that the crosswalk forms a parallelogram and that its area can be calculated in two different ways using the given information. By equating these two area calculations, we can solve for the unknown distance between the stripes.

This approach demonstrates the power of using different perspectives to analyze a geometric problem. By considering the parallelogram from two different angles and using the same area formula, we can set up an equation that allows us to solve for the missing value.
Step 1: Identify the crosswalk as a parallelogram with base 15 feet (the length of the curb between the stripes) and altitude 40 feet (the distance between the parallel curbs).

Step 2: Calculate the area of the parallelogram using the formula: Area = base $\times$ height
$$\begin{align*}
\text{Area} &= 15 \times 40 \\
&= 600\; \text{ft}^2
\end{align*}$$

Step 3: Now, consider the parallelogram from another perspective, with base 50 feet (the length of each stripe) and altitude equal to the distance between the stripes (the unknown value we want to find).

Step 4: Using the same area formula, set up an equation with the unknown distance:
$$\begin{align*}
\text{Area} &= \text{base} \times \text{height} \\
600 &= 50 \times \text{distance}
\end{align*}$$

Step 5: Solve for the distance:
$$\begin{align*}
\text{distance} &= \frac{600}{50} \\
&= 12\; \text{feet}
\end{align*}$$
The distance between the stripes is $\boxed{12}$ feet.

